The latest version is **MSTest 4.2.1** — a major version bump from 3.8.0. Here are the breaking changes that affect **your code specifically**:

### 1. `[ExpectedException]` is removed (build error)

Your two test methods use `[ExpectedException(typeof(...))]`, which was removed in v4. Replace with `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>()`:

```csharp
// Before
[ExpectedException(typeof(ArgumentNullException))]
[TestMethod]
public void Validate_NullInput_ThrowsArgumentNull()
{
    Validate(null);
}

// After
[TestMethod]
public void Validate_NullInput_ThrowsArgumentNull()
{
    Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(() => Validate(null));
}
```

### 2. `Assert.IsTrue(true)` triggers MSTEST0032 warning

The analyzer MSTEST0032 ("condition is always true") is now **Warning** severity (was Info). Your `Validate_ValidInput_Succeeds` test will produce a build warning. Replace with a meaningful assertion or suppress it.

### Other v4 breaking changes (not currently in your code, but worth knowing)

| Change | Impact |
|---|---|
| `TestMethodAttribute.Execute` → `ExecuteAsync` | If you have custom `TestMethodAttribute` subclasses |
| `ClassCleanupBehavior` enum removed | If you use `[ClassCleanup(ClassCleanupBehavior.EndOfClass)]` |
| `TestContext.Properties` is now `IDictionary<string, object>` | `.Contains()` → `.ContainsKey()` |
| `TestTimeout` enum removed | Use `[Timeout(int.MaxValue)]` instead |
| `Assert.ThrowsException` removed | Use `Assert.ThrowsExactly` |
| Assert APIs no longer accept `message` + `params object[]` | Use string interpolation |
| .NET 7 and below dropped | net8.0+ required (you're fine) |

